      <hedline>
        <hl1>For Debates, Three Isn't a Crowd</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sam Husseini letter disputes August 22 editorial, which advocated one-on-one debates between Vice Pres Al Gore and Gov George W Bush as best way to educate voters and spur public interest</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Stop Arguing and Start Debating'' (editorial, Aug. 22) advocates one-on-one debates between Al Gore and George W. Bush as the best approach to educate voters and spur public interest. But recent history suggests otherwise.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Stop Arguing and Start Debating'' (editorial, Aug. 22) advocates one-on-one debates between Al Gore and George W. Bush as the best approach to educate voters and spur public interest. But recent history suggests otherwise.</p>
        <p>In 1992, when Ross Perot was included in the presidential debates, they were watched on average by 90 million TV viewers, with the audience growing for each successive debate. The 1996 debates, limited to Bill Clinton and Bob Dole, had shrinking audiences that averaged 41 million viewers.</p>
        <p>Third-party candidates not only bring fresh issues and viewpoints to the debates, but new viewers and voters as well.</p>
        <p>SAM HUSSEINI  Washington, Aug. 22, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is communications director, Institute for Public Accuracy.</p>
      </block>
